more difficult than usual if the
Palestinians

40:43.608 --> 40:48.946 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
feel the new U.S. administration
has shifted
strongly towards Israel.

40:48.980 --> 40:54.085 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The early days of the Trump
administration
were not comforting to
Palestinians.

40:54.118 --> 40:59.891 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But when Netanyahu announced
another set of
settlement building, the White
House did react.

40:59.924 --> 41:05.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The first part of the statement
signaled a
shift in past policy, often
critical of Israel

41:05.697 --> 41:10.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on the settlement building
issue, saying the
administration doesn't believe
the settlements

41:10.301 --> 41:13.705 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are "an impediment to peace."

41:13.738 --> 41:19.977 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But then a change in tone: "The
construction
of new settlements or the
expansion of existing

41:20.011 --> 41:26.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
settlements beyond their current
borders may
not be helpful in achieving that
goal."

41:26.117 --> 41:29.554 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It was interpreted in Israel as
a polite warning.

41:29.587 --> 41:32.924 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It raised some concern within
the Netanyahu
coalition.

41:32.957 --> 41:39.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Dan Meridor served as a Cabinet
minister under
Netanyahu, but left politics
because of Netanyahu's

41:39.764 --> 41:41.232 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
shift to the right.

41:41.265 --> 41:44.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He says, when it comes to Trump,
the government
shouldn't assume too much.

41:44.969 --> 41:49.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAN MERIDOR, Former Israeli
Cabinet Minister:
Because he's so unpredictable in
a way, I

41:49.607 --> 41:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wouldn't bet anything on what
may develop.

41:53.678 --> 42:00.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If I were the government, I
wouldn't base
any policies on any presumption
Trump will

42:00.618 --> 42:02.453 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
go in a set way.

42:02.487 --> 42:06.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARTIN SEEMUNGAL: White House
statements and
Trump's recent comments do
appear to indicate

42:06.290 --> 42:12.797 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a change in direction from the
first days
of Trump's presidency, more in
line with longstanding

42:12.830 --> 42:18.002 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
American policy based on two
states for two
peoples.

42:18.035 --> 42:23.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The two-state solution is
critical to peace,
because Palestinian Authority
President Mahmoud

42:23.074 --> 42:25.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Abbas still believes it.

42:25.376 --> 42:29.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It remains the foundation of the
Palestinian
dream.

42:29.881 --> 42:34.552 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tomorrow's White House visit by
Netanyahu
will be watched very closely on
both sides

42:34.585 --> 42:41.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Jerusalem and on the West
Bank for any
hint of a change in the status
quo, one defined

42:41.426 --> 42:43.861 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for so long by division.

42:43.895 --> 42:49.834 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm
Martin Seemungal
in Jerusalem.

42:49.867 --> 43:02.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: how a
school district
in Kansas is grappling with the
problems of

43:02.413 --> 43:03.915 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
homeless students.

43:03.948 --> 43:09.086 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PBS special correspondent Lisa
Stark of our
partner Education Week reports.

43:09.120 --> 43:11.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's part of our weekly series
Making the
Grade.

43:11.622 --> 43:13.491 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MAN: Let's go, let's go!

43:13.524 --> 43:15.359 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Keep the ball in bounds!

43:15.393 --> 43:20.731 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LISA STARK: It's varsity
basketball practice
at Schlagle High School in
Kansas City, Kansas,

43:20.765 --> 43:28.439 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and 6'6'' senior Malik Cushon is
the tallest
guy on the team, determined on
the court and

43:28.473 --> 43:30.274 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
off.

43:30.308 --> 43:33.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALIK CUSHON, Student: I just
had to set my
mind to it, had to be focused,
real focused

43:33.110 --> 43:34.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to get back where I needed to
be.

43:34.745 --> 43:38.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Back from a place he
never expected
to find himself.

43:38.483 --> 43:41.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A few months ago, Malik had
nowhere to live.

43:41.919 --> 43:47.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALIK CUSHON: Me and my mother
had a little
miscommunication, and one word
led to another.

43:47.758 --> 43:50.962 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't want to get too deep
into it, because
I still love my mother.

43:50.995 --> 43:55.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it just wasn't right at the
moment, so
she just kicked me out.

43:55.132 --> 43:57.935 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: Did you realize he
was homeless?

43:57.969 --> 43:58.936 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PRENTES POTTS, Basketball Coach,
Schlagle
High School: I didn't know.

43:58.970 --> 43:59.937 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I didn't know.

43:59.971 --> 44:00.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: How did you find
out?

44:00.938 --> 44:01.906 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
PRENTES POTTS: He told me.

44:01.939 --> 44:05.009 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He told me, told me through a
text message.

44:05.042 --> 44:09.881 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: But by the time
Malik told coach
Prentes Potts what was going on,
he was sleeping

44:09.914 --> 44:15.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on a friend's floor and had
missed nearly
a month of school, a common
problem for homeless

44:15.119 --> 44:18.890 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
students, who are more likely to
fall behind
and drop out.

44:18.923 --> 44:22.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALIK CUSHON: If I'm jumping
from place to
place, I'm not as focused on my
school work.

44:22.727 --> 44:24.428 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I got to think about what I'm
eating for the
night.

44:24.462 --> 44:27.064 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I got to think about how bills
are going to
get paid.

44:27.098 --> 44:28.432 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I got to think about all this
extra stuff.

44:28.466 --> 44:31.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
PRENTES POTTS: It kind of -- it
blew me away.

44:31.536 --> 44:32.603 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Excuse me.

44:32.637 --> 44:34.872 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm getting choked up.

44:34.906 --> 44:39.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It blew me away, for the simple
fact is, he
never communicated anything like
that, and

44:39.844 --> 44:41.579 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
his spirits are always so high.

44:41.612 --> 44:44.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You never could tell by looking
at him that
that is what he was going
through.

44:45.016 --> 44:48.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALIK CUSHON: My little sister
and my big
brother.

44:48.419 --> 44:52.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Malik now lives in
housing for
homeless youth, and gets
services from the

44:52.456 --> 44:54.258 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
school district.

44:54.292 --> 44:59.297 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Under federal law, districts
must identify
homeless students, those on the
streets, doubled

44:59.330 --> 45:03.401 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
up in motels and shelters, or,
like Malik,
on their own.

45:03.434 --> 45:06.037 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK, Homeless Liaison:
Did you do
the intake with Ms. Marie?

45:06.070 --> 45:08.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Districts must also
have a homeless
liaison.

45:09.006 --> 45:10.708 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Here, that's Kerry Wrenick.

45:10.741 --> 45:16.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Her job is to make sure homeless
students
have the support they need to
stay in school.

45:16.280 --> 45:22.119 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK: We provide
educational services
to make sure that kids get
enrolled in school,

45:22.153 --> 45:26.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
get transportation back and
forth to school,
and then just kind of ensuring
that their

45:26.490 --> 45:28.125 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
everyday needs are met.

45:28.159 --> 45:31.262 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Student homelessness
is a widespread
problem.

45:31.295 --> 45:36.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nearly one in four school
districts in the
U.S. gets federal grant money to
help provide

45:36.267 --> 45:38.502 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
services for homeless students.

45:38.536 --> 45:40.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And that money is stretched
thin.

45:40.738 --> 45:45.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It amounts to about an average
of about $50
per student.

45:45.209 --> 45:48.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the district also counts on
outside help.

45:48.546 --> 45:50.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK: Everything in
here is donated.

45:50.281 --> 45:55.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: This room overflows
with supplies
for homeless students and
families.

45:55.886 --> 45:58.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is one of the poorest
districts in Kansas.

45:58.856 --> 46:04.462 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This year, the school district
expects to
help more than 1,000 homeless
students, nearly

46:04.495 --> 46:07.365 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
5 percent of the student
population.

46:07.398 --> 46:09.767 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Over time, the solution became
clear.

46:09.800 --> 46:13.771 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To help homeless students, they
needed to
help homeless families.

46:13.804 --> 46:19.710 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK: I had to come to
the realization
that I wasn't doing enough, that
although

46:19.744 --> 46:25.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
everything that I was doing was
well-intended,
I was putting a Band-Aid on
things.

46:25.416 --> 46:32.423 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: In 2015, Wrenick put
out a call
for help; 27 groups responded,
nonprofits,

46:32.456 --> 46:34.125 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
civic groups, state agencies.

46:34.158 --> 46:37.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DESIREE MONIZE, Avenue of Life:
I think the
level of collaboration is very
unusual.

46:37.795 --> 46:43.334 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Desiree Monize runs
Avenue of
Life, a nonprofit that helps
low-income families

46:43.367 --> 46:45.069 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and oversees this collaboration.

46:45.102 --> 46:49.106 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: My oldest daughter, her
school had
referred me to here.

46:49.140 --> 46:51.108 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Here's how it works.

46:51.142 --> 46:55.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once a family is certified by
the school district
as homeless, they can get
assistance through

46:55.780 --> 46:57.815 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a program called Impact
Wednesday.

46:57.848 --> 47:03.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They meet with a case manager,
take classes
on employment, finance and
housing.

47:03.454 --> 47:08.059 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In return, there's help finding
a job and
a home.

47:08.092 --> 47:09.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Pay for transportation,
food and clothing.

47:09.894 --> 47:12.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA STARK: The program has
taken off.

47:12.296 --> 47:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DESIREE MONIZE: We piloted last
year when
the school district opened in
August.

47:16.233 --> 47:22.239 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the close of year one, we
were able to
house 58 families, permanently
house, and

47:22.273 --> 47:26.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
saw a 19 percent reduction in
homelessness
within the district by the close
of year one.

47:26.977 --> 47:34.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: And already this
school year,
65 families settled in homes,
including the

47:34.652 --> 47:39.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
family of second grader Daisy
Swift (ph),
her fifth grade sister, Cece
Tiebout (ph),

47:39.557 --> 47:41.659 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and their mom, Angela Jordan, a
hairdresser.

47:41.692 --> 47:43.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANGELA JORDAN, Mother: You guys
have everything
together?

47:43.427 --> 47:46.831 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: What if the school
district program
hadn't been there to help you?

47:46.864 --> 47:48.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANGELA JORDAN: We wouldn't be
here right now.

47:48.399 --> 47:50.501 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I don't where we would be.

47:50.534 --> 47:54.271 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We'd probably be -- probably be
on the streets
or living in our car.

47:54.305 --> 47:58.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Avenue of Life found
them this
one-bedroom apartment, covered
the deposit

47:58.843 --> 48:00.644 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and one month's rent.

48:00.678 --> 48:05.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The girls attend their original
elementary
school, even though it's not
their neighborhood

48:05.182 --> 48:06.917 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
school.

48:06.951 --> 48:10.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Federal law requires districts
to provide
transportation to the school
students started

48:10.387 --> 48:14.391 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the year in, even if they move
into permanent
housing during the school year.

48:14.425 --> 48:19.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK: To keep one kid
at one school
for one year, we just have the
best outcome

48:20.030 --> 48:24.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
for their learning and their
potential to
pass and go on to the next
grade.

48:24.301 --> 48:27.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANGELA JORDAN: They knew that
that was their
safe zone, you know, that they
could go there

48:27.905 --> 48:31.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and be relaxed and know that
they were fine
there.

48:31.509 --> 48:35.112 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: These transportation
costs do
add up.

48:35.146 --> 48:38.916 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Two years ago, the district
spent $450,000
to transport homeless students.

48:38.949 --> 48:42.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANGELA JORDAN: I will see you
guys after school.

48:42.486 --> 48:47.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: But they reduced
that by more
than 20 percent last year by
finding homes

48:47.858 --> 48:49.026 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for families.

48:49.059 --> 48:51.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Do you have cooking stuff
that's in
your hotel?

48:51.428 --> 48:53.164 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
MAN: No.

48:53.197 --> 48:56.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Kansas City's didn't
start out
to rescue homeless families, but
that's just

48:56.367 --> 49:00.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what happened when they focused
on saving
students.

49:00.404 --> 49:02.606 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What is your goal for these
kids?

49:02.640 --> 49:06.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KERRY WRENICK: To see them
graduate and end
the cycle of homelessness.

49:06.110 --> 49:12.483 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, my greatest blessing
would be for
Malik to graduate and him never
enter the

49:12.516 --> 49:14.251 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
system again.

49:14.285 --> 49:18.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Malik is on track to
become the
first of his siblings to get a
traditional

49:18.155 --> 49:19.857 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
high school diploma.

49:19.890 --> 49:21.792 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Then his plans include junior
college.

49:21.826 --> 49:25.296 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALIK CUSHON: Just me
graduating, walking
the stage is going to be a proud
moment for

49:25.329 --> 49:27.264 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

49:27.298 --> 49:34.405 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: And a proud moment
for the district,
which found that fighting
student homelessness

49:34.438 --> 49:36.941 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
takes a full-court press.

49:36.974 --> 49:45.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Kansas City, Kansas, I'm Lisa
Stark of
Education Week for the "PBS
NewsHour."

49:45.449 --> 49:56.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A remarkable
accomplishment
has taken place now in college
sports.

49:56.093 --> 50:02.967 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The women's basketball team at
the University
of Connecticut has now won 100
straight games.

50:03.000 --> 50:04.835 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
William Brangham has more.

50:04.869 --> 50:08.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: To put this
streak in context,
the UConn women haven't lost a
basketball

50:08.973 --> 50:11.141 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
game since 2014.

50:11.175 --> 50:13.477 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one has beaten them in over
800 days.

50:13.510 --> 50:18.515 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And inside that span, they also
won two of
their record four national
championships.

50:18.549 --> 50:22.686 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One analyst called the UConn
women -- quote
-- "the most dominant program in
the history

50:22.720 --> 50:25.256 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of college basketball, period."

50:25.289 --> 50:29.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on these amazing women
and their
legendary coach, Geno Auriemma,
I'm joined

50:29.193 --> 50:31.262 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
by USA Today's Christine
Brennan.

50:31.295 --> 50:32.529 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Welcome back to the "NewsHour."

50:32.563 --> 50:33.264 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN, USA Today:
Great to be
here, William.

50:33.297 --> 50:34.665 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

50:34.698 --> 50:37.534 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, explain
this phenomenon
that is these women.

50:37.568 --> 50:39.403 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
How do you explain their
dominance?

50:39.436 --> 50:43.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: Well, no one
saw this coming,
if you consider, UConn had won
four national

50:43.440 --> 50:44.808 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
championships in a row.

50:44.842 --> 50:45.809 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
And...

50:45.843 --> 50:46.810 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Amazing, in
and of itself.

50:46.844 --> 50:48.712 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: That's right.

50:48.746 --> 50:53.651 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the top three players from
that, the seniors
who won all four years, all went
in the WNBA

50:53.684 --> 50:55.286 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
draft first, second and third.

50:55.319 --> 50:59.023 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, of all players coming out of
college,
they were the best three.

50:59.056 --> 51:00.424 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
They all left.

51:00.457 --> 51:03.193 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, everyone thought this was
going to be
a down year for UConn.

51:03.227 --> 51:04.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: A rebuilding
year.

51:04.728 --> 51:07.331 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: Exactly, and
expected a
loss or two early in the season.

51:07.364 --> 51:10.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And all of a sudden, UConn is
playing the
best teams in the country, and
they're not

51:10.768 --> 51:12.469 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
losing, and they're winning and
winning and
winning.

51:12.503 --> 51:19.109 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And here we are with this
legendary 100th
victory for a team that is
synonymous with

51:19.143 --> 51:21.178 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
winning, but nothing like this.

51:21.211 --> 51:25.249 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, I think it's really
stunning, because
this was supposed to be, as you
said, the

51:25.282 --> 51:28.419 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rebuilding year, and they have
just reloaded.

51:28.452 --> 51:34.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, again, it's just a great
testament to
a program and a coach, Geno
Auriemma, that

51:34.992 --> 51:38.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is not only just one of the
greatest in the
history of women's sports and
certainly the

51:38.095 --> 51:41.732 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
best in women's basketball, but
I think in
all sports, men's or women's.

51:41.765 --> 51:45.202 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, if you
take the top
three players out of your team
-- and those

51:45.235 --> 51:48.605 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are the top three draft picks,
as you say
-- how do they do this?

51:48.639 --> 51:53.143 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is this -- this obviously is a
testament to
something of the coaching ethos
at that school.

51:53.177 --> 51:54.878 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: Exactly.

51:54.912 --> 51:57.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, Geno Auriemma will always
get three
or four of the best basketball
players in

51:57.848 --> 52:01.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the country every year, but you
only have
a team of 12.

52:01.318 --> 52:05.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's not like he can pick 100
and have them,
stockpile them somewhere in a
gym in Storrs,

52:05.856 --> 52:08.025 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Connecticut, and pull them out
when he wants
to.

52:08.058 --> 52:11.662 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, this is the part, William,
that is just
so amazing to me.

52:11.695 --> 52:15.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Today is the greatest day in
women's sports,
until tomorrow.

52:15.599 --> 52:17.401 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

52:17.434 --> 52:21.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: By that, I
mean Title IX
working its magic, coaching,
parents caring,

52:21.872 --> 52:25.809 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the salaries for coaches, the
training for
girls.

52:25.843 --> 52:29.046 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Everyone knows the girl next
door, their niece,
their daughter.

52:29.079 --> 52:33.384 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You see it every day in this
country now,
such a cultural phenomenon,
girls playing

52:33.417 --> 52:36.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sports, and then of course
women's sports
as well in college and onward.

52:36.954 --> 52:41.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to think that, at this most
competitive
time in the history of women's
sports and

52:41.425 --> 52:47.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
women's basketball, that you
would have one
team dominating like this, it's
truly amazing

52:47.398 --> 52:51.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to me, as a journalist who has
covered sports
all these years, that this is
happening now.

52:51.702 --> 52:54.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What it means is, Geno Auriemma
is such a
great coach.

52:54.505 --> 52:56.073 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He gets these great players.

52:56.106 --> 52:59.910 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then he puts them into a
system where
he demands that they be
teammates.

52:59.943 --> 53:01.712 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They cannot be rock stars,
superstars.

53:01.745 --> 53:03.947 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Yes, they often -- in fact, some
of them become.

53:03.981 --> 53:08.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He wants them to be cogs in a
system that
has worked now for several
decades.

53:08.052 --> 53:12.356 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They buy into it, and they have
championship
after championship to prove it.

53:12.389 --> 53:15.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Lastly, I know
this is an
oft-debated question, but is
this kind of

53:15.592 --> 53:17.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a dynasty good for the sport?

53:17.294 --> 53:18.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I have heard it argued both
ways.

53:18.896 --> 53:22.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, these women blow their
teammates away
-- their opponents, largely.

53:22.733 --> 53:24.068 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
It this good for women's
basketball?

53:24.101 --> 53:25.502 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: I think it's
both good
and bad.

53:25.536 --> 53:28.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One the one hand, dynasties are
fun.

53:28.405 --> 53:30.474 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We just went through the New
England Patriots.

53:30.507 --> 53:32.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People are hoping the Cubs will
become a dynasty.

53:32.176 --> 53:35.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Obviously, you talk to a Yankee
fan, they
love that over the years.

53:35.879 --> 53:38.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
As much as people hate the
Yankees, people
love the Yankees.

53:38.082 --> 53:43.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, I think we're into dynasties
and winning,
Michael Jordan, Tiger Woods, et
cetera.

53:43.087 --> 53:45.289 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think that's certainly a
headline always
in sports.

53:45.322 --> 53:47.724 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so, from that aspect, I
think it's a good
thing.

53:47.758 --> 53:51.929 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The bad part is, it's like, OK,
this is women's
basketball?

53:51.962 --> 53:53.397 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Where is the rivalry?

53:53.430 --> 53:55.132 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Where is the competition?

53:55.165 --> 53:59.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think there is concern --
and I know
I have certainly mentioned it --
that, OK,

53:59.203 --> 54:03.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
again, at this most competitive
time in the
history of women's sports, how
is it possible

54:03.207 --> 54:05.075 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that one team dominates like
this?

54:05.109 --> 54:06.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does it say about the
competition?

54:06.677 --> 54:08.479 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What does it say about the other
coaches?

54:08.512 --> 54:13.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My sense is that UConn may have
a couple more
really great years, but the
history tells

54:13.750 --> 54:16.920 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
us and our culture tells us they
can't keep
this up.

54:16.954 --> 54:20.824 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the Marylands, and the
Baylors, and the
Notre Dames are going to come on
like gangbusters

54:20.858 --> 54:22.059 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in a few years.

54:22.092 --> 54:23.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Christine
Brennan, thank
you so much.

54:23.694 --> 54:25.362 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRISTINE BRENNAN: Thank you,
William.

